metadata.name: Capture Bigfoot - Wild Paper Series #223
metadata.description:
In the wilderness of the Pacific Northwest, a legendary creature hides.  Some have tried to find proof of its existence, but have failed.  Will you be the one to capture evidence of the elusive Bigfoot?  

This generative work features hand-drawn ink sketches that have been digitally enhanced, and assembled into these beautiful vistas of distant mountains, mid-range foothills, stands on conifers, large boulders, . . . and, of course, the elusive Bigfoot.

Draw the super-rare Squatch Card for an extra bonus!

Functions: 
Press SPACE to download and save image as a png.
Click or tap the canvas to toggle full screen.

Squatch Card Special Function:
Press 'V' to view assets layout card.
Refresh token to toggle back to landscape.

metadata.name: Ribbonacci #39
metadata.description:
Interlocking ribbons are placed around focal points like sunflower seeds, using the Golden angle.

Features: six color schemes, two color variation types, three rendering styles, and variable aspect ratios.

----

The Golden angle is based on œÜ ("phi"), the most irrational number. Using this angle between successive ribbons means that as they spiral outwards, they end up distributed evenly around the center. The Golden angle is visible in many plants, not just the sunflower, since it helps prevent leaves from shading each other. ("Fibonacci phyllotaxis")

Phi, the Golden angle, and Fibonacci numbers generally have many fascinating, unexpected, and beautiful mathematical and geometric relationships. Learning about them was a delight.

----

Keys: 1-8 to change pixel density, s or double click to save, S to toggle drop shadows if present.
URL parameters: shadows (0 or 1), animated (0 or 1), aspect (e.g. 16:9, 2:3, 8.5:11)

metadata.name: Collage #46
metadata.description:
Inspired by traditional Japanese wagami design. We use the iconic patterns of our previous projects to recreate this artwork. All the patterns are generated first and then used to build the scene. 

In this project Aluan brings his delicate texture from his 'Chaos' series, Jinyao brings his beloved pattern from the 'Cloud' series and Wen brings his iconic pattern from the 'Maze'. 'Collage' is not just about mixing our style, but it is also about finding harmony among all the elements. 'Collage' is also about working together, in that we can create something that's difficult to achieve or imagine if we were working alone.

Each piece contains the patterns of all the 3 artists, each artist has a certain number of patterns with different colors. Depending which artist you get, his pattern will be shown as the primary color theme while the pattern of the other 2 artists turns into grayscale to make the primary pattern with color stand out. 

There are 7 different scenes included in this project, which are : Mountains, Waves, Lake, Hexagons, Tetrapods, Chrysanthemums and Lotus. We took great inspiration from the traditional Japanese design, and we discovered these are some of the most common elements in it. Therefore we decide to use them and reimagine them by mixing our patterns. 

The title 'Collage' doesn't only apply to the visual style, but also to the code as well. In this project we mixed p5.js and Vanilla JS. While Aluan and Jinyao work with their patterns in p5. Wen gathered the patterns and recreated the full scene in Vanilla JS.
